-- Copper Drops First Day in Four Before China Ends Policy Meeting
-- B y   J a e   H u r
-- 2013-11-12T02:54:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-12/copper-drops-first-day-in-four-before-china-ends-policy-meeting.html
Copper fell for the first time in
four days as investors assessed when the  Federal Reserve  will
begin to reduce stimulus and awaited the conclusion of the
Chinese Communist Party’s four-day policy meeting today.  The contract for delivery in three months on the London
Metal Exchange lost as much as 0.5 percent to $7,135 a metric
ton and traded at $7,135.25 by 11:38 a.m. in  Tokyo . The metal
has declined 10 percent this year.  President Xi Jinping and Party leaders conclude a gathering
aimed at mapping out a blueprint for reform. A report today is
forecast to show confidence among U.S. small businesses fell in
October to match the lowest level since April after data last
week showed U.S. employers added more workers than forecast.  “Investors are waiting for details of China’s reforms
after the policy meeting and trying to assess the timing of a
reduction in Fed stimulus,” said Tetsu Emori, chief  fund
manager  at Astmax Asset Management Inc.  Fed policy makers will pare the monthly pace of bond buying
to $70 billion at their March 18-19 meeting, according to the
median of 32 economist estimates in a Bloomberg News survey Nov.
8.  Copper for delivery in January on the Shanghai Futures
Exchange slid 0.5 percent to 51,400  yuan  ($8,438) a ton. Futures
for delivery in December declined 0.4 percent to $3.465 a pound
on the Comex in  New York .  On the LME, lead and tin dropped, while aluminum, zinc and
nickel were little changed.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jae Hur in Tokyo at 
